# TypeScript Type Safety

## Prisma $transaction with Mixed Model Operations

When batch-updating multiple Prisma models (e.g. Content + Image), do NOT build a `PrismaPromise[]` array — different model operations return incompatible types (`ContentClient[]` vs `ImageClient[]`) that cannot be unified. Use the **callback form** of `$transaction` instead.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD - map+filter(Boolean): null pollutes the array type
const ops = items.map(item => {
  if (item.type === 'content') return prisma.content.upsert({...})
  if (item.type === 'image') return prisma.image.upsert({...})
  return null
}).filter(Boolean)
await prisma.$transaction(ops)

// ❌ BAD - flatMap: ContentClient[] and ImageClient[] are incompatible types
const ops = items.flatMap(item => {
  if (item.type === 'content') return [prisma.content.upsert({...})]
  if (item.type === 'image') return [prisma.image.upsert({...})]
  return []
})
await prisma.$transaction(ops)

// ✅ GOOD - callback form: each operation is typed independently
await prisma.$transaction(async (tx) => {
  for (const item of items) {
    if (item.type === 'content') {
      await tx.content.upsert({...})
    } else if (item.type === 'image') {
      await tx.image.upsert({...})
    }
  }
})
```

## Prefer flatMap over map+filter(Boolean) for Same-Type Results

When filtering and transforming items of the **same type**, use `flatMap` with empty array returns instead of `map` + `filter(Boolean)`.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD - filter(Boolean) does NOT narrow the type
const results = items.map(i => condition(i) ? transform(i) : null).filter(Boolean)

// ✅ GOOD
const results = items.flatMap(i => condition(i) ? [transform(i)] : [])
```

## Avoid Non-null Assertions Without Guards

Do not use `!` (non-null assertion) to silence type errors. Use proper type guards or early returns.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
const user = users.find(u => u.id === id)!
user.name // crashes at runtime if not found

// ✅ GOOD
const user = users.find(u => u.id === id)
if (!user) throw new Error('User not found')
user.name // safe
```

## Explicit Return Types for Conditional Branches

When a function has conditional branches returning different types, ensure all branches are covered and TypeScript can infer a consistent return type. Add explicit return type annotations when inference may be ambiguous.
